SIMPLE: symbolism
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Symbolism
<hw>Sym"bol*ism</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The
act of symbolizing, or the state of being symbolized; <as>as,
<ex>symbolism</ex> in Christian art is the representation of truth,
virtues, vices, etc., by emblematic colors, signs, and
forms</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A system of symbols or representations.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>The practice of
using symbols, or the system of notation developed thereby.</def>
<sd>(b)</sd> <def>A combining together of parts or ingredients.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Theol.)</fld> <def>The science of creeds;
symbolics.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Symbolist</ent>⟦br⟧
